Got a bunch of questions about the fact that our family is Jewish celebrating Hanukkah while having a Christmas tree at home (all out of curiosity and with respect which I always appreciate). Wanted to share the history of my Russian Jewish background to shed some light on this tradition. Back in Soviet Union as it got its communist regime (1922), all religious celebrations and traditions were banned (Christmas was one of them), until 1935 when Stalin decided to bring back aspects of the holiday without the religious focus of it and a new secular holiday was born (for the non orthodox Russians)-Novey God.  Literally translating to "New Year" in Russian, the Novy God holiday became widespread in the Soviet Union and continued to be part of tradition after the fall of communism. The holiday does carry some old traditions, some of which have similarities to many other winter and new year holidays, but they are distinct for being observed secularly. Ded Maroz (father frost- Soviet version of Santa Clause) and Yolka (version of the Christmas tree) are all part of our family’s tradition as well as other Russian Jewish families ❤️ I love the fact that I get to celebrate all aspects of my family’s heritage and teach my kids about the background and meaning of it all 🙏🏻 Merry Christmas, Chag Sameah and S’novem godam 😊

#vlbookclub 📚 A New Earth by Eckhart Tolle. I’ll start by saying I LOVED this book, but it wasn’t a typical reading experience for me. It took me about 1.5-2 years to finish which, in my opinion, is the right pace for a book that carries this depth of insight – ideas that you need time to absorb and reflect on. Rather than reading front-to-back in a matter of days, I chose a more intuitive journey by navigating chapters in a way that felt most relevant to my life at any given moment and going from there. It’s an incredible book if you’re going through anything that is challenging you, forcing you to adjust your expectations, or look at the world through a different lens. This book urges readers to find a new state of consciousness and uncover how ego plays a role in all of our lives, and how it can prevent us from finding fulfilment. I highlyyyy recommend you take your time with this one! Keep it on your nightstand and go back, even to chapters you’ve read before, when you could use a little mindset shift. It’s no wonder this book is renowned as it truly offers some life-changing perspectives. I can’t wait to hear what you all think 🙏🏻

I don’t believe in regrets but I do believe in lessons. One of the biggest lessons I wish I could share with 28 year old Valeria (who just had her 3rd baby) would be to *not* rush back to “normality” and to acknowledge the hidden mental load of motherhood.

I remember how much I downplayed the fact I just had a baby and went right back into work, socializing, and other responsibilities. Trying to be a superhero which carried no novelty. Did I try to prove something to myself? Or to @garylipovetsky? Or to the outside world? I’m not quite sure, but the emotional, mental and physical burnout surely followed. It took me 2 years to start feeling like myself again and set the boundaries I so desperately needed to enforce. 

We may not all be privileged to take a year off to create that environment for healing but even the acknowledgment of where we’re at and what we need can make this season a bit softer and supportive for us mothers ❤️

Each year, I write down something I want to do that really scares me. Hosting my own podcast has been that one thing for the last 3 years. Whenever I picked it up thinking I was ready, I kept feeling like something was off and would inevitably put it down again. I embarked on the journey of building my own product line, @valeriathebrand, by fluke. I was passionate about affordable, high-quality accessories, decided to try offering it to my community, and the brand Leia was born.

We carried jewelry and sunglasses while trying to navigate how to build an e-commerce brand from scratch. Our expertise was always in media so venturing into the side of logistics and manufacturing was the Wild West but we accepted he challenge. Then, COVID hit and prices for materials went up.

We changed course as we couldn’t offer the same pricing for the quality I wanted. Then we introduced active, lounge, and sleepwear and rebranded to Verie. I LOVED seeing my community living in our creations but man, the journey to create anything felt like climbing a mountain with rocks on your back. Nothing humbles you more than thinking you’ve made progress just to find out you’re back to square one.

Coming out of COVID, I really wanted to take a stab at ready-to-wear clothing. Being frustrated with the manufacturing process overseas, we brought production to the US and paid a premium to get it right, leading to another rebrand.

Fast forward 1.5 years later, I’ve realized that – at this point – it was my ego driving the brand and not my heart. Nothing was scarier than admitting this big failure and it felt as scary to ignore the other thriving branches of my business, to invest more energy on the one area that didn’t yield progress anymore.

With this came the decision to wind down @valeriathebrand and refocus on where my passion and expertise lays: media and content.

Since becoming a mother, I feel like I’ve gone through so many seasons.

The first season was with Jake – I was 22, navigating becoming a caregiver and wife – physically, mentally, and emotionally – while still growing up and figuring out my own identity. I was fully in survival mode just trying to fit into what I thought “motherhood” supposed to look like based on what I saw other people doing. I honestly can’t say I remember much of those days.

The second season was with Ben – I was 23, I felt a bit steadier, had a little more experience, and was just starting my self-discovery journey. I loved being present for my 2 little boys. Life was simple but, as time went on, my attention started shifting towards what I wanted to do with my life outside of motherhood.  I had that nagging feeling of “there’s gotta be more” and I began focusing on my professional development and interests. Mom guilt started peeking in.

The third season was with Maximus – I was 28, had a business, and a team that relied on me, and I was fully in a phase of feeling like I had to prove myself day in and day out. I dove back into work right after coming home from the hospital. I operated on zero sleep, a lot of guilt, and an endless amount of ambition and discipline…needless to say, I crashed. I remember fragments of those early days and I remember feeling like I’d have regrets dedicating this much time and effort into work and not my newborn. And I did – for a while.

And now we’re here in what I see as my fourth season. I’m a mother of a 10, 8, and 4-year-old, navigating from a place of experience, lessons, compassion to myself. I call this season: Gentle Motherhood. I’m soaking up the slow and the fast, the bad and the good. No longer chasing abstract definitions of what motherhood needs to look like and fully savouring what is and what it feels like for ME. I don’t think I’ve ever been as present or content with motherhood as I am today – I hope to stay here for a while ❤️

I recently heard of a young couple that hired a couples therapist early on in their relationship. At first, I was a little amused by it; we don’t really hear about couples getting therapy during the “honeymoon stage” when everything is easy and exciting. But then I started thinking about my own experiences realizing that the base of ANY long-term relationship (not just romantic ones!) is finding the right way to express your needs and communicate effectively. Being able to express in a way that doesn’t create a you VERSUS me situation but rather you AND me versus the problem.
Being married for 11 years now, I would say that this is one of the TOP ways to stay in it and continue being devoted to your partner. Can you imagine starting a relationship with someone you want to build a future with, with clarity on how they want to be loved and supported?! 🤯 it eliminates a layer of anxiety, frustration, and teaches you early on about your communication styles. We all come into relationships with our own traumas from childhood, baggage from past relationships and the examples we had growing up (hopefully good ones, if we’re lucky) but prioritizing learning about your individual communication styles – and how you can work TOGETHER – is definitely a way to get ahead of issues that arise from all that existing STUFF.

Picture this:⁠ I’m 18 years old and I’ve been chosen to be featured in a big magazine, shot by an established photographer in the fashion industry. It’s my first big North American job and finally getting a big YES in a job that’s filled with daily NOs is huge validation for a young model. I arrive 30 minutes early to set, an hour goes by, three hours go by, five hours go by, and it’s finally my turn to be in front of the camera. I work extra hard to hype myself up because confidence doesn’t come naturally to me and shooting alongside other known models in the industry can be very intimidating. It goes well and I’m SO excited to see the finished product!⁠
⁠
A few months go by and the spread comes out – I RUN to get myself a copy. These photos will be huge for my portfolio as I set my sights on making it big in the US market. I start flipping through the pages and I can’t find my face. My heart starts beating fast thinking, “oh my god they didn’t include me because I wasn’t as good as the other girls!” I do another scan of the pages and spot a vaguely familiar face – it’s me!! Only with bigger lips, greener eyes, red hair, and a new jaw?⁠
⁠
I remember the moment it hit me – the anger, the disappointment, the punch to my (already low) self-esteem. I realize that, as a model, you’re there to bring someone else’s vision to life. They get to choose how you will be portrayed. But 18 year old me took it so personally – the subtle (and not-so-subtle) photoshopping –because those external perceptions became the voices inside my head. Allowing my self-worth to be dictated by others stripped me of my own power. ⁠
⁠
This experience will forever be a core memory; it was that moment when I decided that I NEEDED to determine my own view of myself, one completely detached from other people’s ideas. I also realized I needed to find new dreams to chase – ones where I get to decide how I’m portrayed and, most importantly, where I get to keep my natural facial structure 😅 Now more than ever, I can’t help but feel grateful for my career and how far I’ve come because I finally feel like I’m exactly where I’m meant to be⁠ 🥹🙏🏻
